\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {43}{\ignorespaces OS-level heterogeneous scheduling: Linux Energy Aware Scheduling (EAS) versus the intelligent OS Capability-Cost Model. EAS (Linux 5.0, 2019) uses an Energy Model to route each task to the most energy-efficient capable CPU and falls back to load balancing under overutilization. The Capability-Cost Model is the direct analog: a Task Director routes each subtask to the optimal compute core (large model, small model, neuromorphic, or biological substrate) by predicted capability, latency, and cost, falling back to the highest-capability core under peak load.}}{86}{figure.caption.144}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:paradigm:scheduling}{{43}{86}{OS-level heterogeneous scheduling: Linux Energy Aware Scheduling (EAS) versus the intelligent OS Capability-Cost Model. EAS (Linux 5.0, 2019) uses an Energy Model to route each task to the most energy-efficient capable CPU and falls back to load balancing under overutilization. The Capability-Cost Model is the direct analog: a Task Director routes each subtask to the optimal compute core (large model, small model, neuromorphic, or biological substrate) by predicted capability, latency, and cost, falling back to the highest-capability core under peak load}{figure.caption.144}{}}
